[32m│[0m ## thoughts                                                                                                                                                                                             [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                                                                                                                                                         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The vulnerability is a classic PHP deserialization + type juggling combination. The app stores user credentials in a client-side cookie using PHP serialization, which allows an attacker to manipulate [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m the data types of the serialized fields. By changing the password field from a string type (`s:N:"value"`) to an integer type (`i:0`), the PHP loose comparison (`==`) between the integer 0 and the    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m stored hash string starting with "0e" evaluates to true because PHP treats "0e..." as scientific notation for 0 in loose comparison context. The boolean true (`b:1`) also works because `true ==       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m "any_nonempty_string"` is `true` in PHP. This is a well-known PHP security anti-pattern combining insecure deserialization (trusting client-side serialized data) with type juggling (using `==`        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m instead of `===`).                                                                                                                                                                                      [32m│[0m
